Heart Failure Prediction Project on dataset (1000)¶

This heart disease dataset is acquired from one of the multispecialty hospitals in India. Over 14 common features make it one of the heart disease datasets available so far for research purposes. This dataset consists of 1000 subjects with 12 features. This dataset will be useful for building early-stage heart disease detection as well as for generating predictive machine-learning models.

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/jocelyndumlao/cardiovascular-disease-dataset

Prepare and load the dataset¶

In [242]:
import pandas as pd
from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# Load dataset
data = pd.read_csv('hf_cardiovascular_disease_1000.csv')

# fill missing values with mean values
data.fillna(data.mean(), inplace=True)

# Define features and target
X = data[['patientid', 'age', 'gender', 'chestpain', 'restingBP',
       'serumcholestrol', 'fastingbloodsugar', 'restingrelectro',
       'maxheartrate', 'exerciseangia', 'oldpeak', 'slope', 'noofmajorvessels']]
y = data['target']

# Apply SMOTE to balance the dataset
smote = SMOTE(random_state=42)
X_resampled, y_resampled = smote.fit_resample(X, y)

# Split data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_resampled, y_resampled, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Scale features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test = scaler.transform(X_test)

from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, roc_auc_score, roc_curve
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Logistic Regression with L2 regularization
lr = LogisticRegression(C=1.0, penalty='l2', solver='liblinear', random_state=42)
lr.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predictions
y_pred_lr = lr.predict(X_test)
y_proba_lr = lr.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

# Evaluation
print("Logistic Regression on dataset")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_lr))
roc_auc_lr = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_proba_lr)
print(f'ROC AUC: {roc_auc_lr:.2f}')

Tuning parameters to mitigate the overfitting and underfitting issue¶

In [254]:
import pandas as pd
from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split, cross_val_score, GridSearchCV
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression, RidgeClassifier, LassoCV
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, roc_auc_score, roc_curve
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier, GradientBoostingClassifier, StackingClassifier
import numpy as np

# Load dataset
data = pd.read_csv('hf_cardiovascular_disease_1000.csv')

# Fill missing values with mean values
data.fillna(data.mean(), inplace=True)

# Define features and target
X = data[['patientid', 'age', 'gender', 'chestpain', 'restingBP',
       'serumcholestrol', 'fastingbloodsugar', 'restingrelectro',
       'maxheartrate', 'exerciseangia', 'oldpeak', 'slope', 'noofmajorvessels']]
y = data['target']

# Apply SMOTE to balance the dataset
smote = SMOTE(random_state=42)
X_resampled, y_resampled = smote.fit_resample(X, y)

# Dimensionality reduction using PCA
pca = PCA(n_components=5)
X_resampled_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_resampled)

# Split data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_resampled_pca, y_resampled, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Scale features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test = scaler.transform(X_test)

# Logistic Regression with more aggressive regularization
lr = LogisticRegression(C=0.001, penalty='l2', solver='liblinear', random_state=42)
lr.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predictions
y_pred_lr = lr.predict(X_test)
y_proba_lr = lr.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

# Evaluation
print("Logistic Regression on dataset with increased regularization")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_lr))
roc_auc_lr = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_proba_lr)
print(f'ROC AUC: {roc_auc_lr:.2f}')

# Cross-Validation
cv_scores = cross_val_score(lr, X_train, y_train, cv=5, scoring='roc_auc')
print(f'Cross-Validation ROC AUC scores: {cv_scores}')
print(f'Mean ROC AUC score: {cv_scores.mean()}')

# Hyperparameter Tuning for Logistic Regression
param_grid = {'C': [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10]}
grid_search = GridSearchCV(LogisticRegression(penalty='l2', solver='liblinear', random_state=42), param_grid, cv=5, scoring='roc_auc')
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Best parameters
best_params = grid_search.best_params_
print(f'Best parameters for Logistic Regression: {best_params}')

# Train Logistic Regression with best parameters
best_lr = grid_search.best_estimator_
best_lr.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predictions
y_pred_best_lr = best_lr.predict(X_test)
y_proba_best_lr = best_lr.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

# Evaluation
print("Logistic Regression with Hyperparameter Tuning on dataset")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_best_lr))
roc_auc_best_lr = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_proba_best_lr)
print(f'ROC AUC: {roc_auc_best_lr:.2f}')

# Ensemble of Different Models
rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=50, random_state=42)
gb = GradientBoostingClassifier(n_estimators=50, random_state=42)

estimators = [
    ('lr', lr),
    ('rf', rf),
    ('gb', gb)
]

stacking_clf = StackingClassifier(estimators=estimators, final_estimator=LogisticRegression())

stacking_clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predictions
y_pred_stacking = stacking_clf.predict(X_test)
y_proba_stacking = stacking_clf.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

# Evaluation
print("Stacking Classifier on dataset")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_stacking))
roc_auc_stacking = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_proba_stacking)
print(f'ROC AUC: {roc_auc_stacking:.2f}')

# Plot the ROC curves
plt.figure()
# Logistic Regression with increased regularization
fpr_lr, tpr_lr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_proba_lr)
plt.plot(fpr_lr, tpr_lr, color='blue', lw=2, label=f'Logistic Regression (AUC = {roc_auc_lr:.2f})')

# Logistic Regression with Hyperparameter Tuning
fpr_best_lr, tpr_best_lr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_proba_best_lr)
plt.plot(fpr_best_lr, tpr_best_lr, color='green', lw=2, label=f'Best Logistic Regression (AUC = {roc_auc_best_lr:.2f})')

# Stacking Classifier
fpr_stacking, tpr_stacking, _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_proba_stacking)
plt.plot(fpr_stacking, tpr_stacking, color='purple', lw=2, label=f'Stacking (AUC = {roc_auc_stacking:.2f})')

plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=2, linestyle='--')
plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve')
plt.legend(loc="lower right")
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split, cross_val_score, GridSearchCV
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression, RidgeClassifier, LassoCV
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, roc_auc_score, roc_curve
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier, GradientBoostingClassifier, StackingClassifier, AdaBoostClassifier
import numpy as np

# Load dataset
data = pd.read_csv('hf_cardiovascular_disease_1000.csv')

# Fill missing values with mean values
data.fillna(data.mean(), inplace=True)

# Define features and target
X = data[['patientid', 'age', 'gender', 'chestpain', 'restingBP',
       'serumcholestrol', 'fastingbloodsugar', 'restingrelectro',
       'maxheartrate', 'exerciseangia', 'oldpeak', 'slope', 'noofmajorvessels']]
y = data['target']

# Apply SMOTE to balance the dataset
smote = SMOTE(random_state=42)
X_resampled, y_resampled = smote.fit_resample(X, y)

# Dimensionality reduction using PCA
pca = PCA(n_components=5)
X_resampled_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_resampled)

# Split data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_resampled_pca, y_resampled, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Scale features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test = scaler.transform(X_test)

# Logistic Regression with more aggressive regularization
lr = LogisticRegression(C=0.001, penalty='l2', solver='liblinear', random_state=42)
lr.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predictions
y_pred_lr = lr.predict(X_test)
y_proba_lr = lr.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

# Evaluation
print("Logistic Regression on dataset with increased regularization")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_lr))
roc_auc_lr = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_proba_lr)

# Hyperparameter Tuning for Logistic Regression
param_grid = {'C': [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10]}
grid_search = GridSearchCV(LogisticRegression(penalty='l2', solver='liblinear', random_state=42), param_grid, cv=5, scoring='roc_auc')
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Best parameters
best_params = grid_search.best_params_
print(f'Best parameters for Logistic Regression: {best_params}')

# Train Logistic Regression with best parameters
best_lr = grid_search.best_estimator_
best_lr.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predictions

y_proba_best_lr = best_lr.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

# Evaluation
print("Logistic Regression with Hyperparameter Tuning on dataset 1000")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_best_lr))
roc_auc_best_lr = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_proba_best_lr)
print(f'ROC AUC: {roc_auc_best_lr:.2f}')

# Ensemble of Different Models
rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=50, random_state=42)
gb = GradientBoostingClassifier(n_estimators=50, random_state=42)
ada = AdaBoostClassifier(n_estimators=50, random_state=42)

    ('lr', lr),

# Convolutional Neural Network (CNN)
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv1D, MaxPooling1D, Flatten

# Reshape data to add timesteps dimension (e.g., timesteps=1)
X_train_cnn = X_train.reshape((X_train.shape[0], X_train.shape[1], 1))
X_test_cnn = X_test.reshape((X_test.shape[0], X_test.shape[1], 1))

# CNN Model
model_cnn = Sequential([
    Conv1D(32, kernel_size=3, activation='relu', input_shape=(input_dim, 1)),
    MaxPooling1D(pool_size=2),
    Dropout(0.5),
    Flatten(),
    Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(0.5),
    Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
])

model_cnn.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Train the model
model_cnn.fit(X_train_cnn, y_train, epochs=50, batch_size=32, validation_split=0.2)

# Predictions
y_pred_cnn = model_cnn.predict(X_test_cnn).ravel()
y_pred_cnn_class = (y_pred_cnn > 0.5).astype(int)

# Evaluation
print("CNN on dataset 1000")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_cnn_class))
roc_auc_cnn = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_cnn)
print(f'ROC AUC: {roc_auc_cnn:.2f}')

# GRU with Attention
from tensorflow.keras.layers import GRU, Attention, Input, Dense, Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model

# GRU with Attention
inputs = Input(shape=(input_dim, 1))
gru_out = GRU(32, return_sequences=True)(inputs)
attention_out = Attention()([gru_out, gru_out])
dropout_out = Dropout(0.5)(attention_out)
gru_out_2 = GRU(16)(dropout_out)
dropout_out_2 = Dropout(0.5)(gru_out_2)
outputs = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(dropout_out_2)

model_gru_attention = Model(inputs, outputs)
model_gru_attention.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Train the model
model_gru_attention.fit(X_train_cnn, y_train, epochs=50, batch_size=32, validation_split=0.2)

# Predictions
y_pred_gru_attention = model_gru_attention.predict(X_test_cnn).ravel()
y_pred_gru_attention_class = (y_pred_gru_attention > 0.5).astype(int)

# Evaluation
print("GRU with Attention on dataset 1000")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_gru_attention_class))
roc_auc_gru_attention = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_gru_attention)
print(f'ROC AUC: {roc_auc_gru_attention:.2f}')

# CNN with GRU

    Conv1D(32, kernel_size=3, activation='relu', input_shape=(input_dim, 1)),
    MaxPooling1D(pool_size=2),
    Dropout(0.5),
    GRU(32, return_sequences=True),
    Dropout(0.5),
    GRU(16),
    Dropout(0.5),
    Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
])

estimators = [
    ('rf', RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)),
    ('gbm', GradientBoostingClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)),
    ('xgbm', XGBClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42))
]

import pandas as pd
from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split, cross_val_score, GridSearchCV
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, roc_auc_score, roc_curve
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from xgboost import XGBClassifier
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, Dropout, Conv1D, MaxPooling1D, Flatten
from sklearn.base import BaseEstimator, ClassifierMixin
import numpy as np

# Custom KerasClassifier wrapper
class CustomKerasClassifier(BaseEstimator, ClassifierMixin):
    def __init__(self, build_fn=None, epochs=1, batch_size=32, verbose=0):
        self.build_fn = build_fn
        self.epochs = epochs
        self.batch_size = batch_size
        self.verbose = verbose
        self.model = None
    
    def fit(self, X, y):
        self.model = self.build_fn()
        self.model.fit(X, y, epochs=self.epochs, batch_size=self.batch_size, verbose=self.verbose)
        return self
    
    def predict(self, X):
        return (self.model.predict(X) > 0.5).astype(int).ravel()
    
    def predict_proba(self, X):
        proba = self.model.predict(X)
        return np.hstack([(1 - proba), proba])

# Load dataset
data = pd.read_csv('hf_cardiovascular_disease_1000.csv')

# Fill missing values with mean values
data.fillna(data.mean(), inplace=True)

# Define features and target
X = data[['patientid', 'age', 'gender', 'chestpain', 'restingBP',
       'serumcholestrol', 'fastingbloodsugar', 'restingrelectro',
       'maxheartrate', 'exerciseangia', 'oldpeak', 'slope', 'noofmajorvessels']]
y = data['target']

# Apply SMOTE to balance the dataset
smote = SMOTE(random_state=42)
X_resampled, y_resampled = smote.fit_resample(X, y)

# Dimensionality reduction using PCA
pca = PCA(n_components=5)
X_resampled_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_resampled)

# Split data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_resampled_pca, y_resampled, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Scale features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test = scaler.transform(X_test)

# Define the CNN model function
def create_cnn():
    model = Sequential([
        Conv1D(32, kernel_size=3, activation='relu', input_shape=(5, 1)),
        MaxPooling1D(pool_size=2),
        Dropout(0.5),
        Flatten(),
        Dense(64, activation='relu'),
        Dropout(0.5),
        Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
    ])
    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

# Reshape data for CNN
X_train_cnn = X_train.reshape((X_train.shape[0], X_train.shape[1], 1))
X_test_cnn = X_test.reshape((X_test.shape[0], X_test.shape[1], 1))

# Custom KerasClassifier wrapper
cnn = CustomKerasClassifier(build_fn=create_cnn, epochs=50, batch_size=32)

# Fit the CNN model first (necessary for stacking)
cnn.fit(X_train_cnn, y_train)

# Define other models
rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
xgbm = XGBClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)

# Fit RF and xGBM
rf.fit(X_train, y_train)
xgbm.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predictions for stacking
y_pred_rf = rf.predict_proba(X_train)[:, 1]
y_pred_xgbm = xgbm.predict_proba(X_train)[:, 1]
y_pred_cnn = cnn.predict_proba(X_train_cnn)[:, 1]

# Combine predictions as new features for the final model
X_train_meta = np.column_stack((y_pred_rf, y_pred_xgbm, y_pred_cnn))

# Train the final meta-model
meta_model = LogisticRegression()
meta_model.fit(X_train_meta, y_train)

# Predictions on the test set
y_pred_rf_test = rf.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
y_pred_xgbm_test = xgbm.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
y_pred_cnn_test = cnn.predict_proba(X_test_cnn)[:, 1]

# Combine predictions as new features for the test set
X_test_meta = np.column_stack((y_pred_rf_test, y_pred_xgbm_test, y_pred_cnn_test))

# Final predictions
y_pred_meta = meta_model.predict(X_test_meta)
y_proba_meta = meta_model.predict_proba(X_test_meta)[:, 1]

# Evaluation
print("Stacking Model (RF + xGBM + CNN) on dataset")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_meta))
roc_auc_meta = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_proba_meta)
print(f'ROC AUC: {roc_auc_meta:.2f}')

# Plot the ROC curves for all models including the new stacking model
plt.figure(figsize=(9, 6))

# Plotting the ROC curves for each individual model
fpr_rf, tpr_rf, _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_rf_test)
plt.plot(fpr_rf, tpr_rf, lw=2, label=f'Random Forest (AUC = {roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_rf_test):.2f})')

fpr_xgbm, tpr_xgbm, _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_xgbm_test)
plt.plot(fpr_xgbm, tpr_xgbm, lw=2, label=f'XGBoost (AUC = {roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_xgbm_test):.2f})')

fpr_cnn, tpr_cnn, _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_cnn_test)

Hyperparameter Tuning¶

  1. Random Forest: Tune parameters like n_estimators, max_depth, min_samples_split, min_samples_leaf.
  2. XGBoost: Tune parameters like n_estimators, max_depth, learning_rate, subsample.
  3. CNN: Tune parameters like epochs, batch_size, and layer-specific parameters like filters, kernel_size, dropout_rate.
  4. Meta-Model: Tune parameters like C in LogisticRegression.

Example Code for Hyperparameter Tuning

Let's use GridSearchCV for hyperparameter tuning.

Tuning Random Forest

# Tuning CNN (Use Random Search due to longer training time)
from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV

def create_cnn(dropout_rate=0.5, filters=32, kernel_size=3):
    model = Sequential([
        Conv1D(filters=filters, kernel_size=kernel_size, activation='relu', input_shape=(5, 1)),
        MaxPooling1D(pool_size=2),
        Dropout(dropout_rate),
        Flatten(),
        Dense(64, activation='relu'),
        Dropout(dropout_rate),
        Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
    ])
    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

# Custom KerasClassifier wrapper with additional hyperparameters
class CustomKerasClassifier(BaseEstimator, ClassifierMixin):
    def __init__(self, build_fn=None, epochs=1, batch_size=32, dropout_rate=0.5, filters=32, kernel_size=3, verbose=0):
        self.build_fn = build_fn
        self.epochs = epochs
        self.batch_size = batch_size
        self.dropout_rate = dropout_rate
        self.filters = filters
        self.kernel_size = kernel_size
        self.verbose = verbose
        self.model = None
    
    def fit(self, X, y):
        self.model = self.build_fn(dropout_rate=self.dropout_rate, filters=self.filters, kernel_size=self.kernel_size)
        self.model.fit(X, y, epochs=self.epochs, batch_size=self.batch_size, verbose=self.verbose)
        return self
    
    def predict(self, X):
        return (self.model.predict(X) > 0.5).astype(int).ravel()
    
    def predict_proba(self, X):
        proba = self.model.predict(X)
        return np.hstack([(1 - proba), proba])

# Define the parameter grid for CNN
param_grid_cnn = {
    'epochs': [20, 50, 100],
    'batch_size': [32, 64],
    'dropout_rate': [0.3, 0.5, 0.7],
    'filters': [32, 64, 128],
    'kernel_size': [3, 5]
}

# Custom KerasClassifier wrapper
cnn = CustomKerasClassifier(build_fn=create_cnn)

# Initialize RandomizedSearchCV
random_search_cnn = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=cnn, param_distributions=param_grid_cnn, 
                                       cv=3, n_iter=10, n_jobs=-1, verbose=2)

# Fit RandomizedSearchCV
random_search_cnn.fit(X_train_cnn, y_train)

# Get the best parameters and model
best_params_cnn = random_search_cnn.best_params_
best_cnn = random_search_cnn.best_estimator_

print("Best parameters for CNN: ", best_params_cnn)

Using the Best Models in Stacking¶

Once you have the best parameters for each model, you can integrate them into the stacking classifier:

In [215]:
# Using the best models from the grid search
rf = best_rf
xgbm = best_xgb
cnn = best_cnn

# Predictions for stacking
y_pred_rf = rf.predict_proba(X_train)[:, 1]
y_pred_xgbm = xgbm.predict_proba(X_train)[:, 1]
y_pred_cnn = cnn.predict_proba(X_train_cnn)[:, 1]

# Combine predictions as new features for the final model
X_train_meta = np.column_stack((y_pred_rf, y_pred_xgbm, y_pred_cnn))

# Train the final meta-model
meta_model = LogisticRegression()
meta_model.fit(X_train_meta, y_train)

# Predictions on the test set
y_pred_rf_test = rf.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
y_pred_xgbm_test = xgbm.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
y_pred_cnn_test = cnn.predict_proba(X_test_cnn)[:, 1]

# Combine predictions as new features for the test set
X_test_meta = np.column_stack((y_pred_rf_test, y_pred_xgbm_test, y_pred_cnn_test))

# Final predictions
y_pred_meta = meta_model.predict(X_test_meta)
y_proba_meta = meta_model.predict_proba(X_test_meta)[:, 1]

# Evaluation
print("Stacking Model (RF + xGBM + CNN) on dataset")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_meta))
roc_auc_meta = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_proba_meta)
print(f'ROC AUC: {roc_auc_meta:.2f}')

More Tuning¶

Additional Steps to Improve Performance¶

  1. Feature Engineering: Create new features based on domain knowledge that might help improve model performance.
  2. Ensemble Methods: Combine more models or use different meta-models.
  3. Deeper Neural Networks: Increase the depth of the CNN or add more complex layers.
  4. Data Augmentation: If applicable, augment the data to increase diversity.
  5. Cross-Validation: Use more folds in cross-validation to get a better estimate of model performance.

Feature Engineering¶

Adding new features or transforming existing features can sometimes significantly improve model performance. For instance, you can try adding polynomial features or interaction terms.

Ensemble Methods¶

We can try combining more models or use different types of models to see if it helps in improving the performance. For instance, adding models like Gradient Boosting or Support Vector Machines (SVM).

import pandas as pd
from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split, cross_val_score, GridSearchCV
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, PolynomialFeatures
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, roc_auc_score, roc_curve
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier, GradientBoostingClassifier
from xgboost import XGBClassifier
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, Dropout, Conv1D, MaxPooling1D, Flatten
from sklearn.base import BaseEstimator, ClassifierMixin
import numpy as np

# Custom KerasClassifier wrapper
class CustomKerasClassifier(BaseEstimator, ClassifierMixin):
    def __init__(self, build_fn=None, epochs=1, batch_size=32, verbose=0):
        self.build_fn = build_fn
        self.epochs = epochs
        self.batch_size = batch_size
        self.verbose = verbose
        self.model = None
    
    def fit(self, X, y):
        self.model = self.build_fn()
        self.model.fit(X, y, epochs=self.epochs, batch_size=self.batch_size, verbose=self.verbose)
        return self
    
    def predict(self, X):
        return (self.model.predict(X) > 0.5).astype(int).ravel()
    
    def predict_proba(self, X):
        proba = self.model.predict(X)
        return np.hstack([(1 - proba), proba])

# Load dataset
data = pd.read_csv('hf_cardiovascular_disease_1000.csv')

# Fill missing values with mean values
data.fillna(data.mean(), inplace=True)

# Define features and target
X = data[['patientid', 'age', 'gender', 'chestpain', 'restingBP',
       'serumcholestrol', 'fastingbloodsugar', 'restingrelectro',
       'maxheartrate', 'exerciseangia', 'oldpeak', 'slope', 'noofmajorvessels']]
y = data['target']

# Apply SMOTE to balance the dataset
smote = SMOTE(random_state=42)
X_resampled, y_resampled = smote.fit_resample(X, y)

# Feature Engineering: Adding Polynomial Features
poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2, interaction_only=True, include_bias=False)
X_resampled_poly = poly.fit_transform(X_resampled)

# Dimensionality reduction using PCA
pca = PCA(n_components=10)
X_resampled_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_resampled_poly)

# Split data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_resampled_pca, y_resampled, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Scale features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test = scaler.transform(X_test)

# Define the CNN model function
def create_cnn():
    model = Sequential([
        Conv1D(32, kernel_size=3, activation='relu', input_shape=(10, 1)),
        MaxPooling1D(pool_size=2),
        Dropout(0.5),
        Flatten(),
        Dense(64, activation='relu'),
        Dropout(0.5),
        Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
    ])
    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

# Reshape data for CNN
X_train_cnn = X_train.reshape((X_train.shape[0], X_train.shape[1], 1))
X_test_cnn = X_test.reshape((X_test.shape[0], X_test.shape[1], 1))

# Custom KerasClassifier wrapper
cnn = CustomKerasClassifier(build_fn=create_cnn, epochs=50, batch_size=32)

# Fit the CNN model first (necessary for stacking)
cnn.fit(X_train_cnn, y_train)

# Define other models
rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
xgbm = XGBClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
gbm = GradientBoostingClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)

# Fit RF, xGBM, and GBM
rf.fit(X_train, y_train)
xgbm.fit(X_train, y_train)
gbm.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predictions for stacking
y_pred_rf = rf.predict_proba(X_train)[:, 1]
y_pred_xgbm = xgbm.predict_proba(X_train)[:, 1]
y_pred_gbm = gbm.predict_proba(X_train)[:, 1]
y_pred_cnn = cnn.predict_proba(X_train_cnn)[:, 1]

# Combine predictions as new features for the final model
X_train_meta = np.column_stack((y_pred_rf, y_pred_xgbm, y_pred_gbm, y_pred_cnn))

# Train the final meta-model
meta_model = LogisticRegression()
meta_model.fit(X_train_meta, y_train)

# Predictions on the test set
y_pred_rf_test = rf.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
y_pred_xgbm_test = xgbm.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
y_pred_gbm_test = gbm.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]
y_pred_cnn_test = cnn.predict_proba(X_test_cnn)[:, 1]

# Combine predictions as new features for the test set
X_test_meta = np.column_stack((y_pred_rf_test, y_pred_xgbm_test, y_pred_gbm_test, y_pred_cnn_test))

# Final predictions
y_pred_meta = meta_model.predict(X_test_meta)
y_proba_meta = meta_model.predict_proba(X_test_meta)[:, 1]

# Evaluation
print("Stacking Model (RF + xGBM + GBM + CNN) on dataset 1000")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_meta))
roc_auc_meta = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_proba_meta)
print(f'ROC AUC: {roc_auc_meta:.2f}')
